subSection.paragraph:
The checklist of Brazilian chiggers listed 63 species of 
Trombiculidae
and 

Leeuwenhoekiidae (
Jacinavicius et al. 2018a
)

. After this, 11 new species have been discovered, 16 previously known species have been reviewed and 21 new records have been reported (
Bassini-Silva et al. 2018a
, 2018b, 2018c, 2019, 2021a, 2021b, 2021c, 2021d, 2021e; 
Jacinavicius et al. 2018b
, 2018c, 2019a, 2019b; 
Sampaio et al. 2020
; 
Arbex et al. 2021
; 
Cousandier et al. 2021
; 
Santos-Rodrigues et al. 2021
). However, despite these studies, information on mite habitats is still lacking for most species. In the present study, a new genus and two new species are described, both collected from Brazilian cave soil. While the hosts are unknown, we suggest these mites are parasitising small rodents or bats that may frequent the caves. The presence of bat guano in the soil suggests the presence of bats. In addition, rodents such as 

Rhipidomys
Tschudi, 1845

(
Rodentia
: 
Cricetidae
) have been recorded inhabiting the iron formation caves in the Carajás region.
